[1] China: National Health Commission 4 May 2020; 82 881 total cases, 4633 deaths
Date: Mon 4 May 2020
Source: China National Health Commission [in Chinese, machine trans., edited]
http://www.nhc.gov.cn/xcs/yqtb/202005/9f8375d7ac9b4eda83515fcd5fd4adf4.shtml


From 0 to 24:00 on [4 May 2020], 31 provinces (autonomous regions and municipalities directly under the Central Government) and Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps reported 1 newly confirmed case (in Shanghai), imported from abroad; no new deaths and no new suspected cases were reported.

On the same day [4 May 2020], 87 new cases recovered and were discharged, 710 close contacts were released from medical observation, and the condition of 4 severe cases improved.

There are 325 confirmed imported cases (including 5 severe cases) and 2 suspected cases. A total of 1676 cases were confirmed, 1351 cases recovered and were discharged, and no deaths [among this group] were reported.

As of 24:00 on [4 May 2020], according to reports from 31 provinces (autonomous regions and municipalities) and the Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps, there were 395 confirmed cases (including 29 severe cases), a total of 77 853 cases were discharged, and 4633 deaths were recorded. A total of 82 881 confirmed cases were reported, and 2 suspected cases are currently [being monitored]. A total of 735 240 close contacts have been traced, and 7152 close contacts were still under medical observation.

31 provinces (autonomous regions, municipalities directly under the Central Government) and Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps reported 15 new cases of asymptomatic infection (no overseas imports); no conversion to confirmed cases; 30 cases under observation were discharged (4 cases imported from abroad); 947 cases of asymptomatic infection (94 cases imported from abroad) are still under medical observation

A total of 1523 confirmed cases were reported from Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan. Among them, there were 1040 cases in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (900 cases discharged and 4 deaths), 45 cases in the Macau Special Administrative Region (39 cases discharged), and 438 cases in Taiwan (334 cases discharged and 6 deaths).

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
and
ProMED-mail rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[According to the report above, a total of 82 881 cases of confirmed COVID-19 have now been reported from mainland China, including 4633 deaths, representing an increase of 1 case in the 24 hours since yesterday's (3 May 2020) report. The newly reported case is in Shanghai and is an imported case. In Hong Kong, where numbers of newly confirmed cases had been reported daily, there was 1 newly confirmed cases reported in the past 24 hours. And Macau has reported no newly confirmed cases. A total of 1676 imported cases have been identified.

As best as I can tell from the machine-translated report above, there were 15 newly confirmed infections in asymptomatic people in the past 24 hours, there were no imported cases. There were no cases of conversion from asymptomatic to symptomatic in the past 24 hours. The total number of asymptomatic individuals currently under observation (and isolation) is 947, and 94 of these are importations from abroad. It would be helpful to know what proportion of asymptomatic infected individuals went on to be symptomatic to start developing projections of actual infection rates and adjust reported case fatality ratios accordingly. It is apparent that there is most likely thorough contact tracing and testing to explain the daily reports of asymptomatic infections in addition to the screening of individuals arriving from overseas.

As reported on 24 Mar 2020, China ended the lockdown in Hubei and elsewhere, and ended it in Wuhan on 7 Apr 2020. There is much caution and skepticism in the media over the reality of the zero case reports. The world is watching carefully to see whether this is safe timing. There do appear to be chains of transmission ongoing in Guangdong (perhaps approaching interruption) and Heilongjiang that are of concern, but clearly the most concerning are the imported cases returning to China.

A map of China showing provinces can be seen at https://sacu.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/provmap.png and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map is available at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7300349,155. - Mod.MPP]

